title: Master of the Nets Garden 网师园
description:
The Master of the Nets Garden (Chinese: 网师园) in Suzhou is among the finest gardens in China. It is recognized with other classical Suzhou gardens as a UNESCO World Heritage Site. The garden demonstrates Chinese garden designers' adept skills for synthesizing art, nature, and architecture to create unique metaphysical masterpieces. The Master of the Nets is particularly regarded among garden connoisseurs for its mastering the techniques of relative dimension, contrast, foil, sequence and depth, and borrowed scenery.

Photo by Sony A7mII + Sony 24-105 F4

description: Silk workers in a factory in Suzhou, China (near Shanghai).  Silk worms occasionally go two to a cocoon rather than singly and then it isn't possible to turn it into thread. title: Silk Factory
description: A silk factory in Suzhou, China (about an hour outside of Shanghai).  They boil the cocoons to extract the dead worm inside and then unwind the very thin threads of silk onto the reels overhead.  Those threads then get combined with others.each worm eats 50 mulberry leaves and it takes 110 cocoons to make enough silk for a tie-- that's a lot of mulberry leaves. (iPhone photo)

title: Reflections of Suzhou
description:
Suzhou, with its many canals and bridges, is often nicknamed the "Venice of the East" (although many other cities often also claim this title as well). 

Being very close to Shanghai has allowed it to become of the fastest growing cities in Mainland China. It is also a popular tourist destination with its many UNESCO sites and attractions, such as this one near Tiger Hill.

title: The many canals of Suzhou
description:
Suzhou, with its many canals and bridges, is often nicknamed the "Venice of the East" (although many other cities often also claim this title as well). 

Being very close to Shanghai has allowed it to become of the fastest growing cities in Mainland China. It is also a popular tourist destination with its many UNESCO sites and attractions, such as this one near Tiger Hill.

description: Not many outside of Mainland China are actually aware that there is a Chinese version of the Leaning Tower of Pisa, Italy. The Tiger Hill Pagoda in Suzhou, which has stood over a millennium has over the centuries slanted by 3 degrees. It is often nicknamed the "Leaning Tower of China".

description:
The Humble Administrator's Garden in Suzhou is one of four Chinese gardens in Suzhou that have attained UNESCO World Heritage Site status, and the most famous and visited among them. 

Its beautiful gardens and huge size makes it a good place to walk an afternoon stroll.

title: Hanshan Temple
description:
Hanshan Temple; literally 'Cold Mountain Temple' is well known because of the poem "A Night Mooring by Maple Bridge", by Tang Dynasty poet, Zhang Ji

月落烏啼霜滿天，
江楓漁火對愁眠。
姑蘇城外寒山寺，
夜半鐘聲到客船。

The moon descends, crows caw, frostiness fills the sky;
riverside maples, fishermen's lights, facing me in my worried sleep.
Outside Gusu city lies Cold Mountain Temple;
at midnight, the sound of bells reaches the ferries.
